@di1214 Ok, I suppose I understand that. I'm working on a considerably smaller team, and our documentation just tells everyone to look at http://awslimitchecker.readthedocs.io/en/latest/limits.html before adding an override. As to the trust issue, we've had occasional problems with AWS Support saying they raised a limit and not actually raising it, or raising the wrong limit or the wrong region. I'm not sure there's really any way around that, for limits that aren't reported via API or Trusted Advisor.

For what it's worth, you may want to look into https://github.com/Yipit/awslimits - I've never used it, but it's a web interface written around awslimitchecker, and I believe it also automatically sets the overrides from support tickets (though that still doesn't account for mistakes by AWS Support).

